      <link>http://www.voiceamerica.com/episode/56229/wisdom-and-the-beauty-of-being-human</link>
      <category>marti spiegelman</category>
      <category>voiceamerica 7th wave</category>
      <category>internet talk radio</category>
      <category>network</category>
      <title>Wisdom and the Beauty of Being Human</title>
      <description>Join me this week for a profound conversation about wisdom, beauty, and being human. To the indigenous mind, the capacity to create is natural to human consciousness, and mastery of consciousness creates, for a culture and all of its members, both a continuity of identity and a dependable pathway of evolutionary thriving through life’s natural cycles of change and transformation. The word art has its origins in the Old French and Latin ars, meaning ‘craftsmanship’. And it’s intriguing to note that those three letters – a-r-t – are also an Old English form of the verb ‘to be’. Even more intriguing are the many early human languages that had neither the verb ‘to be’ nor a word for art. In fact, ‘being’ was originally understood as ‘being conscious’. If you were alive in this world there was no way you could ‘not be’ and an indigenous Shakespeare would have crafted a much different inquiry.</description>
